title: Grateful Dead Live at Music Hall on 1973-12-02
lineage: Maxell UD90 > Nakamichi CR-5A > Edirol FA-66 > Wavelab >R8Brain > CD-Wave > TLH > FLAC 1644 tagged. Transfer by Andrew F.
description: Set 1 Cold Rain & Snow, Beat It On Down The Line, Dire Wolf, The Race is On, Brown Eyed Women, Jack Straw, Ramble On Rose, El Paso, Row Jimmy, Big River, Deal, Weather Report Suite Prelude-> Weather Report Suite Part 1-> Let It Grow Set 2 Wharf Rat-> Mississippi Half Step-> Playin' In The Band-> Mind Left Body Jam-> He's Gone-> Truckin'-> Stella Blue, Sugar Magnolia, E: Morning Dew 'Merry-Go-Round Broke Down' & 'Beer Barrel Polka' tunings before 'Jack Straw". This date is featured on Dick's Picks 14.

reviews.review_text: Amazing!!! Wow! I've been hoping someone would one day make a Matrix of this special and unique. It sounds wonderful. All that I hoped for and more. Very special thanks to dusborne. I am in your debt.
Top Show of 73', great transfer Nice to fill in the gaps from whats missing from DPV.14 too. This matrix really brings the show to it's best possible transfer. Thanks for this!
Diggin' these matrices Very cool sound with the AUD overlaying the SBD.  Very slow Cold Rain and Row Jimmy, time to kick back with a jazzy cigarette.
12/2/73 Playing with the best mlb, good matrix!

Grateful Dan. Another fine matrix from D.Usbourne,whos name has become synonymous with great matrix recordings(and cool pictures) just as Charlie Millers name is to the best soundboards..The boards from most shows sound a bit flat and soulless to me,give me a good AUD or better still Matrix,anyday..The shows great,again with a 2nd set thats got everything:Playin>mlb jam,wharf rat,truckin and a beautiful Hes gone..No wonder Dick loved 73 so... This late 73 show is a prelude of whats to come in 74..Get on it!
Banter after Brown-Eyed Women Love when the boys are feeling loose enough to pull shit like 6 minute long tuning breaks

December 73' This show is a really nice addition to anyone's 73' collection.
The first set is gr8 buildup to a killer second set.Highly recommended!!!

What a treat This show is a top 10 for sure. Glorious from start to finish. They're feeling loose and exploratory. At the peak of their game. With some banter, too. 

And the sound is special. I love being able to feel the vibe of the audience but while also having really clear sound through the instruments. Superlative. Take some time and be merry!

PITB The playin'->MLB that kicks off the meat of the 2nd set is one of the best you'll ever hear. The deranged, ever-so-curious improvisation on this segment really takes you into the belly of the beast and back. A must-listen pair for all deadheads, truly. 
This matrix sounds incredible, by the way. 
Other highlights, he's gone->truckin'->stella->sugar mag is full of red-hot GD meat. Nasty versions of BEW, jack, and let it grow. Amazing wharf rat on this concert, you can feel the pathos seeping in on it. And i also loved the row jimmy (one that i love every time). Great show, you'd be better off hearing both nights from DP14 in their entirety rather than just sticking to that, there's a lot of gold in here!

A 2nd Set jam so epic, you can't fit it onto one CD Realistically, this is more of a 4.5 star for me because the 1st set is pretty standard fare, though it still has plenty more juice than the whole 12/1/73 gig, but I think this 2nd set is one of the clear highlights of '73 followed by a pretty good Sugar Magnolia and a top shelf Morning Dew. Wharf Rat is probably the highlight of the night for me, one of the finest they've done.

Amazing show and best sounding recording I can find. I love these '70s matrixes. For my money, this is the best (or one of the best) recordings of this legendary show. I like this one better than the Dick's Picks soundboard.

Of course, I don't need to say much about the show itself. It's the stuff of legends! The second set is quite possibly one of the best of the year. Wharf Rat is warm and full of psychedelic gooey goodness. During this 3-night run in Boston, the Dead played PitB on every single night. The first night as a set 1 closer jam (that goes on about 23 minutes, but not as exciting as the other big Playin's of the year). The second night as a part of an explosive Playin>UJB>Playin' sequence in the second set. But this one, the third night, goes into some deep explorations. Not exactly uncharted, but also not exactly explored a lot. The transition between the Playin' jam into a sound/noise/feedback jam is immaculately clean. And just when you think it's winding down, Bobby starts strumming those familiar chords. They bring it all back home with one of the best MLB jams of the year, and quite possibly of all time! From the depths of the underworld to Paradise in a matter of minutes with the Dead as your tour guide.

He's Gone>Truckin>Stella & Sugar Mag finish up the set in grand fashion before a Morning Dew encore to wrap up the run (with the song bookending the run as well as it was the opener on 11/30).

As far as '73 Dead goes, I'm not sure it gets much better than this one. To paraphrase Dean Moriarty/Neal Cassady; This is IT.

Recording gets a 5/5 and the show gets a 5/5.

Always loved B. Music Hall!! Drove up from NY, had tix for all 3 shows. Nothing short of remarkable, the jams, the transitions are just sooo smooth and tasty. All reviews agree here- 2nd set hit a level not always reached, this night they were on another planet. I was too, but I know the sound of something very special. Seeing the boys since 70’ I can remember plenty of shows, but this one has burned a memory so sweet in my head.There is something about the end of year shows that seems to sparkle every year. Dec. 73’ they were flying just about every show. Only thing better is listening to the show again.
Peace to all….
